<h1>Adverbs of Degree</h1>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
Japanese adverbs can precede adjectives or verbs to modify them.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{totemo}}}} is an adverb that precedes the adjective it is modifying. It is used in affirmative sentences
to mean "very".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{pekinn}}ha@EM{{@HI{{totemo}}}}@KJ{{cold}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Beijing is very cold.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{amari}}}} is an adverb that precedes the adjective it is modifying. It is used in negative sentences
to mean "not very".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sakura@KJ{{large^study}}ha@EM{{@HI{{amari}}}}@KJ{{possess^name}}na@KJ{{large^study}}jaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Sakura Univeristy is not a very famous university.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

<p>
@HI{{yoku}}, @HI{{daitai}}, @HI{{takusann}}, @KJ{{few}}@HI{{shi}}, @HI{{amari}} and @KJ{{whole^sort*of*thing}}
are adverbs of degree and amount that precede verbs to modify them. The tables below show the degree of modification and whether they are used
in affirmative or negative sentences.

<table class="example">
 <tr>
   <th> Degree </th>
   <th> Affirmative </th>
   <th> Negative </th>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> high </td>
   <td> @HI{{yoku wakarimasu}} </td>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
   <td> @HI{{daitai wakarimasu}} </td>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> low </td>
   <td> @HI{{sukoshi wakarimasu}} </td>
   <td> @HI{{amari wakarimasenn}} </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
   <td> @HI{{zenzenn wakarimasenn}} </td>
 </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

<table class="example">
 <tr>
   <th> Amount </th>
   <th> Affirmative </th>
   <th> Negative </th>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> large </td>
   <td> @HI{{takusann arimasu}} </td>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> small </td>
   <td> @HI{{sukoshi arimasu}}</td>
   <td> @HI{{amari arimasenn}} </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
   <td> &nbsp; </td>
   <td> @HI{{zenzenn arimasenn}}</td>
 </tr>
</table>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{england^word}}ga yoku wakarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I understand English very well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{england^word}}ga @KJ{{few}}shi wakarimasu.}}      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I understand English a little.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{england^word}}ga amari wakarimasenn.}}      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't understand English so well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{gold}}ga takusann arimasu.}}      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I have a lot of money.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{gold}}ga @KJ{{whole^sort*of*thing}}arimasenn.}}      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't have any money.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
Note that @HI{{sukoshi}} and @HI{{zenzenn}} can also modify adjectives.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kokoha@KJ{{few}}shi@KJ{{cold}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It's a little cold here.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}ha@KJ{{whole^sort*of*thing}}omoshirokunaidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That film isn't at all interesting.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>


